1.1. Test for Heteroskedasticity

#Method 1. Graph the residuals
olsfit <- lm(lwage ~ exp+wks+ed, data=wagedata)
summary(olsfit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = lwage ~ exp + wks + ed, data = wagedata)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -2.17762 -0.24556  0.00879  0.26802  2.01027 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 5.1272683  0.0667767  76.782  < 2e-16 ***
## exp         0.0131608  0.0005786  22.746  < 2e-16 ***
## wks         0.0064961  0.0012073   5.381 7.83e-08 ***
## ed          0.0765796  0.0022746  33.667  < 2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.3993 on 4161 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2519, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2514 
## F-statistic: 467.1 on 3 and 4161 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
residual <- residuals(olsfit)

plot(residual~wagedata$ed, xlab="Education", ylab="Residuals")

plot(residual~wagedata$exp, xlab="Experience", ylab="Residuals")

#Method 2. Breusch-Pagan Test
#install.packages("lmtest") #Install this first if you don't have the package
library(lmtest)
bptest(olsfit)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  olsfit
## BP = 25.402, df = 3, p-value = 1.273e-05

1.2. Clustered SE

#Robust: this will generate the same result as stata
# import the function from repository
url_robust <- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/IsidoreBeautrelet/economictheoryblog/master/robust_summary.R"
eval(parse(text = getURL(url_robust, ssl.verifypeer = FALSE)),envir=.GlobalEnv)

summary(olsfit)$coefficient
##                Estimate   Std. Error   t value      Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept) 5.127268310 0.0667766981 76.782298  0.000000e+00
## exp         0.013160758 0.0005785915 22.746198 4.730966e-108
## wks         0.006496111 0.0012072883  5.380745  7.825867e-08
## ed          0.076579640 0.0022746025 33.667263 5.653216e-220
summary(olsfit, robust = T)$coefficient
##                Estimate   Std. Error   t value      Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept) 5.127268310 0.0762716287 67.223795  0.000000e+00
## exp         0.013160758 0.0006570677 20.029531  2.827305e-85
## wks         0.006496111 0.0013132028  4.946769  7.843467e-07
## ed          0.076579640 0.0023887053 32.059058 9.783614e-202
#Robust = c("HC3", "HC", "HC0", "HC1", "HC2", "HC4", "HC4m", "HC5"),
#clustered SE: just plug in the varible name into the cluster
coeftest(olsfit, vcov = vcovHC(olsfit, cluster = "education"))
## 
## t test of coefficients:
## 
##              Estimate Std. Error t value  Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 5.1272683  0.0765081 67.0161 < 2.2e-16 ***
## exp         0.0131608  0.0006577 20.0102 < 2.2e-16 ***
## wks         0.0064961  0.0013179  4.9291 8.581e-07 ***
## ed          0.0765796  0.0023912 32.0256 < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

2. Panel Estimation

#install.packages("plm")
#library(plm)

Set the group and time variables

same as xtset in Stata, the same id and the t should have no more than one observations.

Group: individual : id

Time: year: t

pdata <- plm.data(wagedata, index=c("id","t"))
## Warning: use of 'plm.data' is discouraged, better use 'pdata.frame' instead
pdata <- pdata.frame(wagedata,index = c("id","t"), drop.index = TRUE)

Pooled OLS estimator

pooling <- plm(lwage ~ exp+wks+ed, data=pdata, model= "pooling")
summary(pooling, robust = T)$coefficient
##                Estimate   Std. Error   t-value      Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept) 5.127268310 0.0667766981 76.782298  0.000000e+00
## exp         0.013160758 0.0005785915 22.746198 4.730966e-108
## wks         0.006496111 0.0012072883  5.380745  7.825867e-08
## ed          0.076579640 0.0022746025 33.667263 5.653216e-220
coeftest(pooling, vcov = vcovHC(pooling, cluster = "group"))
